article.headline: Key 18-2 second-half run helps Jayhawks pull away
article.linkText: Kansas starts rough but rolls to eighth straight win
article.story: LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) -- It's never fun to get chewed out, especially with about 16,000 people looking on. Nevertheless, a good tongue-lashing by coach Roy Williams was apparently just what No. 14 Kansas needed Saturday. After Williams pulled the five starters and yelled at them for a few minutes, Kirk Hinrich ignited the slow-starting Jayhawks and got them rolling to a 92-59 victory over Nebraska. "I think we responded pretty well,'' said Hinrich, who scored 28 points and helped fuel an 18-0 run to start the second half. "We always listen to him.'' Said point guard Aaron Miles, "I think it was just what we needed.'' The Jayhawks (11-3, 2-0 Big 12) missed 13 of their first 16 shots before getting the hang of things and winning their eighth straight overall and their 22nd straight regular-season conference game. "I don't think we came out focused,'' Williams said. "I don't think we came out ready to play.'' Nebraska (8-6, 0-1), which had won three in a row, lost point guard Jake Muhleisen early in the game. The Huskers' second-leading scorer at almost 13 points a game, he was injured after crashing to the floor while going in for a layup. He later rejoined his teammates on the bench but did not return to the game. "He has a back injury and groin injury,'' coach Barry Collier said. "He is in bad shape. His back is out of alignment.'' Collier said Muhleisen still had not been ruled out for Wednesday's game against Texas A&M. Hinrich scored nine of Kansas' last 11 points in the first half, and then the Jayhawks went on the 18-0 run after the Huskers scored the first basket of the second half. "We played pretty well for about 30 minutes,'' Hinrich said. Kansas' reserves were only in the game for a couple of minutes but the Jayhawks stayed cold a while longer. At one point, Hinrich and Nick Collison threw up back-to-back air balls. "When I put our starters back in, it still wasn't pretty,'' Williams said. Nebraska, meanwhile, missed 10 of its first 14 shots and never got ahead by more than a point despite the Jayhawks' problems. "It was pretty hard,'' said Nate Johnson, who filled in at point guard for the Huskers. "We put our heads down and didn't get back in the game. When Jake went down, I knew there was going to be a lot of pressure on me.'' About 4½ minutes before halftime, Miles fed Collison underneath for a layup and the 6-foot-10 senior, who missed his first six shots, completed a three-point play. That started an 18-7 run as the Jayhawks took a 40-28 halftime lead. Keith Langford had 18 points for the Jayhawks, who hit their first 20 free throws en route to their eighth straight victory over Nebraska. Collison finished with 10 points. Jeff Graves, in his second start in place of injured Wayne Simien, had 11 points and 12 rebounds. Johnson and Brian Conklin each had 12 points for Nebraska, which has lost its last seven Big 12 openers.
